# UDP Throughput Experiments

## Disclaimer

This repository contains personal investigations around UDP performance and packet processing.

It is made available publicly for educational and experimental purposes only. It is not related to GATTACA SOFTWARE.

Some initial scaffolding was accelerated with LLM assistance. The experiment design, profiling direction, bottleneck analysis, and iteration decisions are my own.

---

## Overview

The goal of this project is to investigate what "kernel bypass" really buys in practice for UDP workloads:

- packets per second (PPS)
- throughput
- latency
- jitter

The approach is deliberately simple:

1. build a clean UDP baseline first,
2. identify the first real bottleneck,
3. only then compare against more advanced paths such as kernel bypass.

At this stage, the focus is on understanding the behavior of the standard kernel/socket path before moving to alternatives such as DPDK or AF_XDP.

---

## Repository Status

This is an experiment repository, not a polished networking framework.

The code is intended to support controlled measurements and bottleneck isolation. Some parts are intentionally simple.

---

## Usage

A helper script, `run_udp_test.sh`, is provided to run the UDP receiver and sender locally and aggregate performance statistics such as:

- packets per second
- throughput in Mb/s

Running both ends on the same machine removes public network bandwidth as a confounding factor and makes it easier to study the OS/kernel path itself.

---

## Build

### CMake (macOS)

Build in release mode:

```bash
cmake -B cmake-build-release -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
cmake --build cmake-build-release

### From Makefile
make clean
make all
make run